---
import BaseLayout from "../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Corrections and Content Review Policy"
  seoTitle="Corrections Policy | Australian Home Collective"
  description="How Australian Home Collective reviews reported issues, corrects significant errors and keeps published guides and planning tools current."
>
  <header class="page-intro">
    <div class="narrow">
      <p class="eyebrow">Accuracy and accountability</p>
      <h1>Corrections and Content Review Policy</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        We review substantive reports and correct inaccurate, outdated or unclear information
        appropriately.
      </p>
    </div>
  </header>

  <section class="content narrow">
    <h2>Our commitment</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective aims to publish practical, accurate and trustworthy
      information that helps Australians make better home-planning and buying decisions.
    </p>
    <p>
      Despite careful editorial review, mistakes can occur and information can become outdated
      as products, specifications, official guidance and manufacturer requirements change. When
      this happens, we are committed to reviewing the issue and correcting the publication
      appropriately.
    </p>

    <h2>Reporting an issue</h2>
    <p>We welcome reports about:</p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>incorrect or outdated information</li>
      <li>broken or misdirected links</li>
      <li>unclear or potentially misleading wording</li>
      <li>important omissions</li>
      <li>accessibility barriers</li>
      <li>unexpected behaviour in a planning tool</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Use our <a href="/contact/">contact page</a> and include the page address and enough
      detail for us to understand the issue. Every substantive report will be reviewed,
      although we may not be able to respond individually to every message.
    </p>

    <h2>How we assess corrections</h2>
    <p>We consider:</p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>the accuracy and source of the reported information</li>
      <li>current manufacturer documentation</li>
      <li>authoritative Australian guidance where relevant</li>
      <li>whether the issue changes the advice or outcome materially</li>
      <li>the potential effect on a reader's decision or safety</li>
      <li>whether related pages or tools may contain the same issue</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Minor spelling, grammar, formatting and broken-link corrections may be made without a
      public correction note.
    </p>

    <h2>Significant corrections</h2>
    <p>
      When a significant factual error is confirmed, we aim to correct it as soon as reasonably
      practicable. Depending on the issue, we may:
    </p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>correct or remove wording</li>
      <li>add a clarification or limitation</li>
      <li>revise a recommendation</li>
      <li>correct tool logic or suspend a tool while it is investigated</li>
      <li>update related guidance</li>
      <li>add a visible correction note where readers would benefit from knowing what changed</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Content reviews</h2>
    <p>Published content is reviewed periodically to improve:</p>
    <ul class="feature-list">
      <li>accuracy and current references</li>
      <li>clarity and readability</li>
      <li>practical usefulness</li>
      <li>internal links and related guidance</li>
      <li>accessibility</li>
      <li>explanations of assumptions, risks and limitations</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      Reviews may also be triggered by changes to a product category, updated manufacturer or
      official guidance, material reader feedback, a correction made to related content, tool
      or browser changes, or evidence that readers are misunderstanding a page.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorially reviewed dates</h2>
    <p>
      Where displayed, an <em>Editorially reviewed</em> date means the content has undergone a
      genuine editorial assessment. It does not necessarily mean every sentence changed.
      Review dates are not updated automatically and are not changed for trivial formatting
      edits alone.
    </p>

    <h2>Tool corrections and incidents</h2>
    <p>
      Reports of incorrect calculations, misleading results, data loss or other material tool
      failures are prioritised according to potential reader impact. Where necessary, we may
      temporarily disable a tool or affected feature while it is investigated. A corrected tool
      must be retested before release.
    </p>

    <h2>Editorial responsibility</h2>
    <p>
      Australian Home Collective is responsible for the content it publishes. Where uncertainty
      exists, we aim to explain the limitation rather than present an assumption as fact.
    </p>

    <h2>Continuous improvement</h2>
    <p>
      Improving existing content is an ongoing part of our editorial process. Guides may be
      expanded or refined as better sources, practical considerations and reader feedback become
      available.
    </p>
    <p>
      Our goal is not simply to publish more. It is to maintain a resource readers can return to
      with confidence when planning purchases for their homes.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
